**Singapore Bi-lateral trend with major trading partners**

The ribbon chart conveys the same message as the bubble chart. In February 2020, a significant decline in imports and exports between Singapore and China could be recognized. In terms of import and export rates, trade between Singapore and China has been well balanced. In 2021, Singapore will likely export more to China.

Malaysia demonstrates an unexpected tendency. Prior to the start of Covid-19, commerce between Singapore and Malaysia was balanced. Since the Covid-19 outbreak, however, Singapore has had a trade deficit with Malaysia.

Covid-19 appears to have little effect on Singapore imports from Taiwan. Taiwan's import volume keeps on growing steadily.

Export from Singapore to Hong Kong has a minimal effect, as there is no discernible change in trend, but the export rate is projected to rise in 2021.

Imports and exports with Indonesia decreased significantly at the beginning of 2020.
:::

## Observe trade dynamic of Singapore's major trading partners in relative

The slope graph allows us to see how each country's import and export dynamics change in relation to the other countries over time.

This code creates two slope plots to display the total import and export values for five countries (China, Malaysia, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Indonesia) from 2016 to 2022.

The first step for both plots is to subset the original data frame to only include the five countries of interest, and then add columns for month and year extracted from the "MonthYear" column. The resulting data frame is then grouped by country and year, and the total import or export value is calculated for each group using the **`summarise()`** function.

After this, the data frame is manipulated to ensure that the "Year" column is ordered correctly and is a factor variable.

For the import plot, the **`newggslopegraph()`** function is used to create a slope plot with the year on the x-axis and the total import value on the y-axis. The plot is titled "Total Import per Year" with a subtitle of "2016-2022", and the **`annotate()`** function is used to add a yellow rectangle highlighting the period from 2020 to 2022.

The same process is repeated for the export plot, with the only differences being the function and plot titles, and the addition of a yellow rectangle to highlight the same period from 2020 to 2022.

**Step 1. Prepare data for slope graph**


```{r slopegraph1, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
# Import
slopeimport <- wide %>% 
  subset(Country == "China" | Country == "Malaysia" | Country == "Taiwan" | Country == "Hong Kong" | Country == "Indonesia" ) %>% 
  mutate(month = month(MonthYear)) %>% 
  mutate(year = year(MonthYear)) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  group_by(Country, year) %>% 
  summarise(sumyear = sum(ImportValue)) %>% 
  mutate(Year = factor(year)) %>% 
  arrange(`sumyear`)

#Export
slopeexport <- wide %>% 
  subset(Country == "China" | Country == "Malaysia" | Country == "Taiwan" | Country == "Hong Kong" | Country == "Indonesia" ) %>% 
  mutate(month = month(MonthYear)) %>% 
  mutate(year = year(MonthYear)) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  group_by(Country, year) %>% 
  summarise(sumyear = sum(ExportValue)) %>% 
  mutate(Year = factor(year)) %>% 
  arrange(`sumyear`)
```


**Step 2. Create slope plot**


```{r slopegraph2, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
#| layout-ncol: 2
#| fig-height: 6
#| fig-width: 5
# Create slope plot for import
p <- newggslopegraph(dataframe = slopeimport, 
                Times = `Year`, 
                Measurement = `sumyear`, 
                Grouping = `Country`,
                Title = "Total Import per Year",
                SubTitle = "2016-2022",
                Caption = NULL)

p + annotate("rect", 
             xmin = "2020", 
             xmax = "2022", 
             ymin = -1, 
             ymax = 600000,
             alpha = .1,
             fill = "yellow")

# Create slope plot for export
p2 <- newggslopegraph(dataframe = slopeexport, 
                Times = `Year`, 
                Measurement = `sumyear`, 
                Grouping = `Country`,
                Title = "Total Export per Year",
                SubTitle = "2016-2022",
                Caption = NULL)

p2 + annotate("rect", 
             xmin = "2020", 
             xmax = "2022", 
             ymin = -1, 
             ymax = 600000,
             alpha = .1,
             fill = "yellow")
```


::: callout-tip
**Trade dynamic of Singapore's major trading** **partners in relative**

The import rankings have remained unchanged, with China maintaining its top position consistently. However, Singapore has increased its imports from three countries, including China, Malaysia, and Taiwan, since 2020.

On the export side, the ranking has also remained steady, with China remaining the top exporter. While China experienced a slowdown in export growth in 2019, it showed accelerated growth in 2021, much like Hong Kong. Malaysia and Indonesia, on the other hand, saw a significant drop in export volumes in 2020 before bouncing back in 2021.
:::

## Observing the dynamic of trade balance based on location

This code is creating an animated choropleth map using the **`tmap`** package in R.

First, the **`World`** data set is loaded, which contains the geographic information for countries. The **`select`** function is used to keep only the columns **`iso_a3`**, **`name`**, **`sovereignt`**, and **`geometry`**. The resulting data frame is stored in the **`map`** variable.

Then, the **`name`** and **`sovereignt`** columns in **`map`** are converted to character type using **`as.character`**.

Next, the **`full_join`** function is used to combine the **`map`** data with the **`wide`** data by matching the **`sovereignt`** column in **`map`** with the **`Country`** column in **`wide`**. The resulting data frame is stored in **`data_map_area`**. The **`drop_na`** function is then used to remove any rows with missing values.

The **`tmap_mode("view")`** sets the mode to view mode to enable interactive viewing of the map.

The **`tm_shape`** function is used to create a **`tmap`** object from the **`data_map_area`** data frame. The **`tm_polygons`** function is used to create the choropleth map by mapping the **`Diff`** variable to the color of the polygons.

The **`tm_facets`** function is used to create an animated map by grouping the data by the **`MonthYear`** column and setting **`free.coords = FALSE`** to keep the same scale across all frames.

Finally, the **`tmap_animation`** function is used to create an animated GIF of the choropleth map with a delay of 50 milliseconds between frames. The resulting GIF is saved as **`choropleth.gif`**.

**Step 1. Prepare data for Choropleth map**


```{r choropleth1, output=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
data("World")
map <- World %>% 
  select(iso_a3, name, sovereignt, geometry)
  

map$name <- as.character(map$name)
map$sovereignt <- as.character(map$sovereignt)
```


**Step 2. Create animated map**


```{r choropleth2, output=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
data_map_area <- map %>% 
  full_join(wide, by = c('sovereignt' = 'Country')) %>% 
  drop_na()
                          
tmap_mode("view")
choropleth <- tm_shape(data_map_area) +
  tm_polygons("Diff") +
  tm_facets(along = "MonthYear", free.coords = FALSE)

tmap_animation(choropleth , filename = "choropleth.gif", delay = 50)
```


